<br>
Please visit our website at www.mikensports.com.  Miken bats are compliant<br>
with ASA, NSA and ISA equipment standards.  At the time the bats were sold,<br>
they were compliant with USSSA standards.  The Ultra II has not been<br>
submitted for approval in 2003 USSSA play under the new 2003 USSSA<br>
performance standard.  The 2003 USSSA performance standard is not approved<br>
by the American Society for Testing and Materials.  The USSSA has also<br>
chosen not to grandfather any bats approved under the former 2002 USSSA<br>
performance standard.  If you have any questions as to why the USSSA has<br>
chosen to change their standard or why they are not grandfathering the Ultra<br>
II under their previous standard, please call USSSA at 804-732-4099 or<br>
e-mail gwusssa@aol.com.<br>
<br>
Because the Ultra II was compliant with the USSSA performance standard under<br>
which it was designed, Miken will not be exchanging or refunding bats.<br>
----------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
--------------------------------<br>
<br>
Frequently Asked Questions about Miken and the new 2003 USSSA Performance<br>
Standard<br>
<br>
Question:  Is the Ultra II approved for 2003 USSSA play?<br>
<br>
Answer:  The Velocit-E Ultra II (MSU2) is not on the USSSA 2003 approved bat<br>
list.<br>
<br>
Question:  Is my Ultra II &quot;grandfathered&quot; for use in 2003 USSSA play?<br>
<br>
Answer:  Though the Ultra II  was designed and approved under the 2002 USSSA<br>
Performance Standard.  USSSA has decided not to &quot;grandfather&quot; it for 2003<br>
play.<br>
<br>
Question:  If the Ultra II is not approved for USSSA play, can I exchange it<br>
for another bat or claim a refund?<br>
<br>
Answer:  The Ultra II was designed to not exceed the USSSA performance<br>
standard in the model year it was submitted.  Because the USSSA changed this<br>
standard after the bat was submitted for original approval, Miken will not<br>
be exchanging or refunding the Ultra II for USSSA non-approval.  The Ultra<br>
II is still approved for use in ASA, ISA and NSA play.<br>
<br>
Question:  What is the difference between the 2002 USSSA performance<br>
standard and the new 2003 USSSA performance standard?<br>
<br>
Answer:  The 2002 USSSA performance standard was derived using ASTM standard<br>
F-1890, where bat performance was measured at the Center of Percussion<br>
(COP), generally considered the sweet spot of the barrel.<br>
<br>
The 2003 USSSA performance standard attempts to measure bat performance over<br>
the length of the barrel using ASTM standard F-1890.  ASTM standard F-1890<br>
is designed to measure bat performance only at the COP.  The new methodology<br>
is not approved by ASTM International.  No data has been presented to Miken<br>
showing the new standard's validity.<br>
<br>
Question:  Is Miken going to make a USSSA approved bat for 2003?<br>
<br>
Answer:  Miken is constantly involved in heavy R&amp;D.  If a future Miken bat<br>
is compliant with the new 2003 USSSA, Miken will look into submitting it for<br>
USSSA approval.<br>
<br>
Question:  Are past Miken bats approved for 2003 USSSA play?<br>
<br>
Answer:  Miken has not been able to test prior models for compliance and<br>
therefore has not submitted any prior models for 2003 USSSA play.<br>
<br>
Question:  Is Miken going to warrant the Ultra II under the original Factory<br>
Warranty in 2003?<br>
<br>
Answer:  The Ultra II will be subject to the 2002/2003 Miken Factory<br>
Warranty.<br>
<br>
Question:  What is the ASTM International?<br>
<br>
Answer:  ASTM International is a global forum for the development of<br>
consensus standards.<br>
<br>
ASTM is a not-for-profit organization that provides a forum for the<br>
development and publication of voluntary consensus standards for materials,<br>
products, systems, and services. ASTM's members, representing producers,<br>
users, consumers, government, and academia from over 100 countries, develop<br>
technical documents that are a basis for manufacturing, management,<br>
procurement, codes, and regulations. These members belong to one or more<br>
committees, each of which covers a subject area such as steel, petroleum,<br>
medical devices, property management, consumer products, and many more.<br>
<br>
For over a century, industries around the world have turned to ASTM<br>
International for the development of voluntary consensus standards. Known<br>
for their high technical quality and market relevance, these standards are<br>
an important part of the information infrastructure that guides design,<br>
manufacturing, and trade in the global economy.<br>
<br>
<br>
